# Rust Comment Strategy

- Prefer self-documenting code first; add comments only when the "why" is not obvious from names, types, and structure.
- Use `//` comments for design rationale, protocol constraints, concurrency assumptions, UTF-16/range conversion details, workarounds, and other non-obvious trade-offs.
- Library crates must document public APIs with `///` and keep `#![warn(missing_docs)]` at the crate root.
- Binary crates should not receive blanket `///` coverage. Prefer brief `//!` docs at the crate root and major modules, plus targeted `//` why-comments in tricky logic.
- In `vhs-analyzer-lsp`, prioritize `//!` docs for `main.rs`, `server.rs`, and `hover.rs`, and use `//` comments for protocol behavior, cached-tree reuse, UTF-16 position mapping, and hover context resolution.
- Avoid comments that narrate obvious control flow or duplicate the code.
- If a binary-crate `pub` item becomes a stable reusable API across crates, promote it to proper `///` documentation instead of leaving it as an implementation detail.

```rust
// GOOD: explains why the transport must stay separated
// LSP traffic owns stdout, so tracing must stay on stderr.

// BAD: repeats what the code already says
// Create the server.
```
